In my current project, there are a LOT of tables. Each one contains form input fields in some of the columns. 
In order to extract the text out of them, I add a parser once in a js file (textExtract option isn't sufficient since it is per column, and I would have to write that code over and over for each table since the columns are not guaranteed to be the same in each one). this fixes all my sorter problems universally.

I ALSO use the output widget on most of these tables. What I am unfortunately forced to do is duplicate the code I use for the parser and place it in "output_formatContent" option (otherwise the fields with inputs have no output data in them). This means I have to maintain the same code in two places. 

It would be nice if the "parsed" option wasn't just filter widget specific. OR, if we could define that widgets should use different parsers. something like:

```
.tablesorter({
    widgets: [
        "output": [
            "parsers": [
                "myCustomParser"
            ]
        ]
});
```

Just SOME way to be able to apply a parser to a widget

I was having some issues outputting a CSV with multiple header rows, some of which included colspan attributes. I resolved the issue by modifying my local widget-output file, but I wanted to share the issues I was having here. 

The issue was that the colspan headers were being repeated an appropriate amount of times, except for the first cell, which was repeating twice instead of the specified four times. My issue was in the process colspans section of the code. 

When looping through to colspanLen, it starts from an index of one 
for (col = 1; col <= colspanLen; col++)

Then when it was supposed to increase the cellIndex count based on the number of filled cells in this line
while (typeof tmpRow[rowIndex][cellIndex] !== 'undefined') { cellIndex++; }
it would start from index of zero. Since the colspan iteration starts from 1, the element in the 0 position of the temporary row was always undefined, and would break the loop. 

The solution that has worked for me is to change the colspan iteration to be zero indexed. 
for (col = 0; col < colspanLen; col++)

The `void` response `type` forces a body to be returned, which goes against the spec of HTTP 204 No Content (and other codes that require an empty body):

> The 204 response MUST NOT include a message-body
> --- http://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616/rfc2616-sec10.html

The problem lies in the `body is None` check:

```python
def validate_outgoing_response(response, schema_map, resolver):
...
    body = prepare_body(response)
    # Short circuit if we are supposed to not validate anything.
    if schema_map.response_body_schema.get('type') == 'void' and body is None:
        return
```

which is can only occur if the body exists and is a JSON encoded `null`:

```python
def prepare_body(response):
    # content_type and charset must both be set to access response.text
    if response.content_type is None or response.charset is None:
        raise HTTPInternalServerError(
            'Response validation error: Content-Type and charset must be set'
        )

    if 'application/json' in response.content_type:
        return simplejson.loads(response.text)
    else:
        return response.text
```

In addition to allowing an empty-body, `void` should also allow the `content_type` and `charset` not to be specified.

